releases/0/tender/title: Cornwall & The Isles of Scilly - Local Enterprise Partnership Area
releases/0/tender/description:
The Provider is expected to deliver the Provision across the whole of Cornwall and the Isles of Scilly. Cornwall and the Isles of Scilly are a large, mostly rural geographical area which includes economically vibrant areas alongside areas of considerable deprivation. As a minimum the Provider must deliver from premises in Penzance, Helston, Redruth (Camborne or Pool), Truro, St Austell, Bodmin, Liskeard and Launceston. Service delivery under this contract is expected to commence in October 2016 and continue until September 2019. There will be a further 64 week payment tail. The contract value is £11,610,000 and there is a requirement for a minimum of 4947 Participants to start on this provision. The aim of this provision is to provide a package of flexible and personalised support to targeted unemployed and inactive Participants to enhance their engagement with the labour market and work readiness and enable them to enter sustained employment. The Provision will be delivered through a series of interventions which will focus on the specific needs of the individual. The Provider must meet ESF specific requirements set by the European Commission and failure to comply can result in a high financial risk for both the Provider and DWP, as funds used inappropriately or for ineligible Participants or purposes and/or where the ESF requirements have not been met are recoverable from Providers. The Provider will use the Provider Referral and Payment (PRaP) system to receive their referrals and to record claimant activity. The Provider will therefore need to have met relevant security requirements when contracts go live. This contract will be for the use of the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP), its Executive Agencies and those Non-Departmental Public Bodies (NDPBs) sponsored by DWP. Further information including a list of such Agencies and Public Bodies can be viewed by selecting 'Ministerial Departments' on the Departmental website.

Additional information: The Contracting Authority intends to use an eTendering system in this procurement exercise. Suppliers Instructions How to Express Interest in this Tender~: 1. Register your company on the eSourcing portal (this is only required once): https://dwp.bravosolution.co.uk and click the link to register - Accept the terms and conditions and click 'continue' - Enter your correct business and user details - Note the username you chose and click 'Save' when complete - You will shortly receive an email with your unique password (please keep this secure) 2. Express an Interest in the tender - Login to the portal with the username/password - Click the 'PQQs / ITTs Open To All Suppliers' link. (These are Pre-Qualification Questionnaires or Invitations to Tender open to any registered supplier) - Click on the relevant PQQ/ ITT to access the content. - Click the 'Express Interest' button at the top of the page. - This will move the PQQ /ITT into your 'My PQQs/ My ITTs' page. (This is a secure area reserved for your projects only) -You can now access any attachments by clicking 'Buyer Attachments' in the 'PQQ/ ITT Details' box 3. Responding to the tender - Click 'My Response' under 'PQQ/ ITT Details', you can choose to 'Create Response' or to 'Decline to Respond' (please give a reason if declining) - You can now use the 'Messages' function to communicate with the buyer and seek any clarification - Note the deadline for completion, then follow the onscreen instructions to complete the PQQ/ ITT - There may be a mixture of online and offline actions for you to perform (there is detailed online help available) You must then submit your reply using the 'Submit Response' button at the top of the page. If you require any further assistance please consult the online help, or contact the eTendering help desk. This is a procurement for services under the Light Touch Regime and DWP will not be bound by Public Contracts Regulations 2015 except as such Regulations are applicable to the Light Touch Regime. DWP expressly reserves the rights: (i)to use a reverse auction; (ii)to cancel this procurement at any stage; (iii)to not award any contract as a result of the procurement process commenced by publication of this notice; (iv)to make whatever changes it may see fit to the content and structure of the tendering competition; (v)and in no circumstances will DWP be liable for any costs incurred by potential suppliers. The Provider will use the Provider Referral and Payment (PRaP) system to receive their referrals and to record claimant activity. The Provider will therefore need to have met relevant security requirements when contracts go live.

releases/0/tender/title: DFID 7249 Somalia Stability Fund Evaluation
releases/0/tender/description:
Actual CPV code is ‘75211200 Foreign Economic-Aid Related Services’.

The specific objectives of the evaluation are:

i.	To evaluate the relevance, effectiveness, efficiency and sustainability of a sample of SSF interventions, including conflict sensitivity and risk mitigation measures. 

ii.	To evaluate to what extent each approach (area-based, sector/partner-based, Government Window, and Rapid Disbursal Projects) is perceived to be relevant and making an effective individual and overall contribution to the two SSF outputs and SSF outcome.

iii.	To evaluate in a number of geographic areas (perhaps 4-5), to what extent SSF projects are perceived to be a coherent portfolio of relevant interventions, making an effective individual and aggregate contribution to the two SSF outputs locally and SSF outcome, given the local context.

iv.	To assess how the SSF has been tracking results both within and outside the DFID logframe and to propose robust measures for the future SSF II, including on gender. 

v.	To use the evaluation evidence to elaborate options for more detailed theories of change (with the SSF team if needed) for different SSF approaches which will be of value for the SSF II.

It is expected that the study should focus on a small number of geographic areas and the programming in those places. The programming to be evaluated would include projects from the 4 categories described above (government window, area based, sector based and rapid disbursal). Likely areas for fieldwork include Kismayo, Baidoa, Central regions, Mogadishu and Puntland.

releases/0/tender/title: DFID 40082831 Support to the Design of a New Bangladesh Urban Poverty Reduction Programme
releases/0/tender/description:
Actual CPV code is '75211200 Foreign Economic-Aid-Related Services'.

Aim and Objectives

The aim of the consultancy contracted under this ToR is to assist DFIDB to design the new urban programme (total approximate cost £60m most likely over about 6 years).  

It will do this by:

•	building on challenges, opportunities and options identified in the scoping report; 
•	undertaking more detailed analysis of key sectors (see below) and considering how a DFIDB programme might be able to support positive outcomes in these areas; 
•	consulting with the GoB, donors active in the area and other Bangladesh stakeholders  to consider how any new DFID B programme will complement existing and planned initiatives  - including whether there should be a standalone new DFID programme or a DFID programme  scaling up existing or planned programmes of others; and
•	considering and providing recommendations on the appropriate institutional home and management structure for any new programme.  

The design mission will need to consider how best to integrate resilience to climate change into the programme.  DFIDB would expect a basic level of inclusion across the programme.  However, there is potential for specific/additional finance specifically on issues of resilience and climate change.  Therefore the design team are asked to also consider how resilience might be scaled up, providing three main options in some detail:

•	The ‘basic’ level of integration of resilience within the programme;
•	A ‘medium’ level of scale up beyond the basic level of integration (e.g. with £10 million); and
•	A more ambitious level of scale up look like (e.g. with £20 million).

releases/0/tender/description:
The Borough Council of Newcastle-under-Lyme and Stafford Borough Council as part of their waste strategy programme are seeking tenders for the composting of Green Waste. The Contractor is to supply a composting site(s)/transfer facility(s) for the acceptance of green garden materials and Municipal green waste to be composted.
The contract shall be let in two lots, with Lot 1 effective from no later than 01.07.2016 to 01.07.2020 with a possible extension of two, two year periods, upon successful delivery and agreement; and Lot 2 effective from no later than 04.02.2016 to 03.02.2018 with a possible extension of three, two year periods, upon successful delivery and agreement

This includes an appropriate waste management licence issued by the Environment Agency and other related permissions associated with composting operations. The compost produced shall meet a recognised standard and shall be marketed as a product designed for use in the private or public gardening sector or alternatively used beneficially on land for the improvement of agriculture and where possible made available within the local communities to each respective Council.

releases/0/tender/description:
NHS Arden & Greater East Midlands Commissioning Support Unit (Arden & GEM CSU) on behalf of NHS England (Midlands and East), are seeking suitably qualified and experienced providers to bid to deliver dental services in Leicester, Leicestershire, Rutland, Lincoln, Lincolnshire. The procurement is split in to lots.

The expectations are that these services will offer increased patient access and funding will be linked to KPI achievement within the current budgets. The successful provider(s) will need to demonstrate that they can deliver continuously high-quality services and will be responsive to the needs of the local populations.  Provider(s) will be assessed on an on-going basis to ensure they deliver the high-quality services required.

These services must be provided by Dentists and Dental healthcare professionals, the provider(s) will be expected to:

•	Deliver primary care dental services which will be accessible, convenient and responsive and/or
•	Deliver special care dentistry services which will be accessible, convenient and responsive,
•	Design services around the needs of patients and carers, ensuring they are offered more choice and a greater say in their treatment,
•	Have processes in place to evaluate and continually improve on patient satisfaction.

This opportunity will be open to the entire market. It should be noted that whilst current providers are able to bid, the contracts being offered will remain separate from each other and any contracts a bidder may currently hold or be bidding for. 

The services will need to be mobilised for and commence on 01st December 2016. Subject to Efficiency Control Committee (ECC) approval, the contracts' end dates will be 30th November 2023, with the option to extend (subject to performance and commissioner decision). Should the ECC, of NHS England, not approve the length proposed of these contracts the relevant parties shall be notified as soon as possible.

Please ensure you download and read all the documentation published with the tender and regularly check the messages facility and documentation area in case of publish of further information.
The Invitation to Tender (ITT) documentation was made available on 29th January 2016 and should be completed and all bids submitted by the closing date of 5pm on 15th March 2016. 
All submissions will be evaluated using the scoring criteria which is contained within the ITT -Document 1.
Clarifications may be asked during the procurement process, the deadline for clarification questions is 5pm on 8th March 2016. 
All correspondence relating to this procurement throughout all stages of the process must be managed through the Arden & Greater East Midlands Commissioning Support Unit (Arden and GEM CSU) eTendering Procurement Portal bravosolutions only.

Additional information: Providers wishing to submit an ITT to deliver this service can do so by logging onto Arden and GEM CSUs procurement portal (Bravo) as soon as possible at: https://ardengemcsu.bravosolution.co.uk/web/login.html 

To register on the portal:

releases/0/tender/title: Request for Information - Intermediate Ear, Nose and Throat (ENT) Services in Croydon
releases/0/tender/description:
Croydon CCG  is seeking information from providers of Ear, Nose and Throat (ENT) services which it will use to help refine its commissioning approach and inform the development of its service specification. 
Croydon CCG is engaging early with potential service providers for an intermediate Ear, Nose and Throat (ENT) service. 
The aim of this exercise is to gauge interest in this opportunity and field for innovative or competitive proposals to improve our local provision. Feedback from the market will help determine our procurement strategy including whether a competitive procurement process is appropriate. 

Local Context

NHS Croydon PCT (now CCG) commissioned a community based “one-stop shop” Intermediate ENT service in 2013, via two Any Qualified Provider (AQP) contracts.
The Intermediate ENT service is to provide:
•	Triage of all ENT GP referrals (currently done by  CHS); and
•	Diagnosis and treatment for non-urgent, benign ENT conditions.

The consultant-led Intermediate ENT service treats:
•	Otalgia
•	Otorrhoea
•	Aural Toilet
•	Otitis Externa
•	Otitis Media
•	Impacted ear wax removal
•	Perforation of eardrum
•	Mastoid cavities requiring evaluation and toileting
•	Tinnitus 
•	Dizziness/vertigo
•	Nasal blockage ± facial pain
•	Nasal polyps
•	Chronic Rhinitis
•	Nose Bleeds (Epistaxis) 
•	Glue ear
•	Snoring
•	Globus (no suspicion of cancer intermittent, non smoker, no weight loss)
•	Intermittent hoarseness >3 weeks

The total contract value for 14-15 was roughly £160k. 

Request for Information (RFI) Questionnaire

Croydon CCG would like to hear views, suggestions and proposals from interested providers as part of this market engagement exercise. If providers would like to contribute please read the provided draft service specification and use the attached Request for Information questionnaire for your submission.  
Responses should be provided as a single document and should not exceed 2,500 words. Submissions in excess of this word limit may not be read. All submissions will be treated confidentially. 
The deadline for submissions is 5pm on 12 February 2016.

Citizens’ Panel for Camden Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG)

Involvement of local residents (some of whom are current patients) in commissioning and service development is fundamental to an integrated, high value health and care system.  
Camden CCG is looking to procure an organisation to recruit and engage  a representative group of Camden residents to act as a local health/care panel to provide regular feedback to the CCG. The Provider will be expected to recruit to and  refresh Panel membership in Year 2 of the contract.  A minimum of 1,000 Camden residents must be recruited.  Panel membership details must be shared with the CCG.  The contract length is two years with a maximum contract value of £80,000 for the two year term.

releases/0/tender/title: Support Services for Children and Young Adults with Palliative Care Needs
releases/0/tender/description:
NHS Arden and Greater East Midlands CSU (NHS Arden & GEM CSU) on behalf of NHS Nottingham West, Nottingham North and East, Rushcliffe and Nottingham City Clinical Commissioning Groups (referred to as the Commissioners) are inviting suitably qualified and experienced providers to deliver Support Services to Children and Young People with Palliative Care Needs.
A Part B open process will be undertaken with a view to awarding the contract for Support Services for Children and Young People with Palliative Care Needs with services commencing from 1st July 2016 for  a period of 2 year 9 months with the option to extend for a further 24 months.
The Commissioners are looking for a provider to deliver high quality, patient centred and value for money (VFM) support service for children and young people with palliative care needs, delivered in a safe and effective manner and through a learning environment which includes the training of all relevant personnel. 

To provide a service designed to support the needs of a child or young person with a life limiting condition and complex health needs. Support will be provided from birth to 18 years of age with the aim of enriching the lives of families and children.
Provision of a holistic family based support service will promote family resilience to impact positively on the child’s well-being. This support should improve quality of life for the child/young person and support their care being maintained within the family for as long as possible.
The  support team will work closely with the wider palliative care team and provide sensitive, skilled and practical support on an individual basis (home or hospital/hospice based), or through groups (e.g. parents and sibling groups) and one off activities, events and outings.
The service will also support the wider family members by providing emotional support to parents and siblings. Support will be provided to the family unit throughout the journey from when a child is first diagnosed with a condition to the bereavement stages.

Additional information: The Contracting Authority intends to use an eTendering system in this procurement exercise The services to which this notice relates fall within Part B of Schedule 3, Part 10 of the Public Services Contracts Regulations 2006 (as amended) ('the Regulations'). Neither the publication of this notice nor the employment of any particular terminology nor any other indication shall be taken to mean that the contracting authorities intend to hold themselves bound by any of the Regulations save those applicable to the procurement of Part B services. These opportunities may be divided into lots. Please see published documentation for further detail. Suppliers Instructions How to Express Interest in this Tender: 1. . Register your company on the e-Sourcing portal (this is only required once) — e-Sourcing Portal: https://ardengemcsu.bravosolution.co.uk/web/login.html and click the link to register— Accept the terms and conditions and click ‘continue' — Enter your correct business and user details —Note the user-name you chose and click ‘Save' when complete — You will shortly receive an e-mail with your unique password (please keep this secure) 2. Express an Interest in the tender — Login to the portal with the user-name/password — Click the ‘ITTs Open To All Suppliers' link. (These are Invitations to Tender open to any registered supplier) — Click on the relevant ITT (itt_355) to access the content. — Click the ‘Express Interest' button at the top of the page. — This will move the ITT into your ‘My ITTs' page. (This is a secure area reserved for your projects only) — You can now access any attachments by clicking ‘Buyer Attachments' in the ‘ITT Details' box 3. Responding to the tender — Click ‘My Response' under ‘ITT Details', you can choose to ‘Create Response' or to ‘Decline to Respond' (please give a reason if declining) — You can now use the ‘Messages' function to communicate with the buyer and seek any clarification — Note the deadline for completion, then follow the on-screen instructions to complete the ITT — There may be a mixture of on-line and off-line actions for you to perform (there is detailed on-line help available) You must then submit your reply using the ‘Submit Response' button at the top of the page. If you require any further assistance please consult the on-line help, or contact the e-Tendering helpdesk

releases/0/tender/title: Employment Support in Primary and Community Care Trial
releases/0/tender/description:
Islington CCG are looking to procure an experienced ‘Individual Placement and Support Provider’ (IPS) to deliver a 24 month trial across Primary and Community Care Services in Islington.  This trial forms part of an overall programme of work being undertaken in relation to Health and Employment in Islington approved by the Health and Wellbeing Board in July 2015 (full details here: - 

http://democracy.islington.gov.uk/ieListDocuments.aspx?CId=143&MId=2635

The trial is seeking to test the effectiveness of the IPS model when applied in a primary and community care setting for people who are unemployed due to a health condition and/ or disability. The service provider will need to be recognised by the Centre for Mental Health as either an existing or emerging ‘Centre of Excellence’ in the delivery of the IPS model and be able to demonstrate high fidelity to the IPS model. The service provider will be expected to work with people with a range of health conditions (both physical and mental health conditions) and / or disabilities in a range of healthcare settings. 

NHS England will be commissioning an independent evaluation of the trial and the provider will be expected to work with the evaluators to ensure that the service delivery model supports the trial requirements and evaluation process.

The service provider will also be expected to be a key partner in the Islington Health and Employment programme. 

Potential applicants wishing to participate in Contracting Authority’s Procurement must have registered an expression of interest and submit an ITT by 1200 noon on 26/02/2016 via the Pro-Contract e-tendering portal at https://www.supplying2nhs.com .

The Commissioner / CCG reserves the right (at its sole discretion) not to consider any Expression of Interests and ITTs received after the deadline.

releases/0/tender/title: DS144-15 Supply and Retrofit of Auxiliary Batteries
releases/0/tender/description:
The Authority is seeking to appoint a Contractor to supply and retrofit auxiliary batteries to a number of their operational vehicles. The auxiliary batteries are required to support the communication equipment.

The contract will be for the supply and retrofit of auxiliary batteries to Medium Rescue Pumping Appliances (MRP‘s) and may include a second optional phase of retrofits to Special Vehicles (Prime Movers, Rescue Tenders, Water Carriers, Operational Support vehicles etc.).

DSFRS currently has 110 MRP‘s and 48 Special Vehicles within its fleet of vehicles (including national resilience vehicles). DSFRS does not intend to retrofit auxiliary batteries to all MRP‘s, only those with a remaining operational life that justifies the investment. Although not confirmed, it is likely that a minimum of 40 MRP‘s will require retrofitting. At this early stage, it is not known how many Special Vehicles would be retrofitted if DSFRS proceeded with the second optional phase.

To maintain operational resilience, the Authority will only release four vehicles for retrofit at any one time.

Potential Providers are able to bid for this requirement based on the following options:

• Option 1 – The auxiliary battery retrofits are carried out at the Contractors Premises (requiring the Contractor to collect and deliver the Vehicles and have their own (or access to) suitable Premises to carry out the Service).
• Option 2 – The auxiliary battery retrofits are carried out at the Authority’s Premises. 

Potential Providers are able to submit a tender based on being able to deliver both of these options or one option only.  The Authority will decide which option to award, once the tender evaluation stage is complete – It will be at the Authority’s discretion as to which option is awarded.

The contract will be awarded to a single Contractor and will only be open and available for the use of Devon and Somerset Fire and Rescue Service.  The relatively low value of the Contract and cap of four vehicles that the Authority can release at any one time is considered achievable for all organisation sizes (including Small and Medium Enterprises).

The contract is anticipated to commence in June 2016. 

Procurement documentation can be found on the Authority‘s e-tendering portal located at https://uk.eu-supply.com/login.asp?B=BLUELIGHT

The deadline for Potential Providers to confirm attendance at the on-site vehicle surveys is on or before Tuesday 23rd February 2016 via the messaging area within the e-tendering portal - https://uk.eu-supply.com/login.asp?B=BLUELIGHT

The date for the on-site vehicle surveys is Wednesday 2nd March 2016, at:

Devon and Somerset Fire and Rescue Service
Knights Road
Chelston Business Park
Wellington
Somerset
TA21 9JH

See tender documentation (Part A - ITT Supporting Information, section 1.6) for further information on vehicle surveys.

Contract start and end dates provided within this advert are indicative only.

releases/0/tender/title: DBC (AL) Print Management Software
releases/0/tender/description:
Dacorum Borough Council (The Council) is seeking to purchase a print management system that will run as a corporate solution, enabling the centralisation of outgoing print tasks with the intent to cut costs, improve efficiency and assist in the move towards home and remote working for council staff whilst supporting a change in the way we communicate with customers, based upon their preferences, with an emphasis on encouraging electronic methods. 

Some of the required features are below:

	The ability for back office users to select jobs to print to either the councils printing software or central print room device, ad hoc and on demand
	Override of employees printing choice where any jobs meet a specific criteria (ie. if job is above >20 pages/colour rather than B&W etc) to the central print room devise/print queue
	A form of ‘print portal’ for planned reprographic jobs, inc. a work ticketing system and print queue management/monitoring facility 
	Interface with Northgate’s Information@Work (the Council’s corporate EDRMS) and our future CRM (Most likely based on MS Dynamics).
	Must work through our homeworking system, Citrix.

The Council will be moving to a new building ‘The Forum’ by January 2017. In response to this move and to support the Council’s Digital Dacorum programme, there is a greater need for a more responsive system, one which will enable us to reduce the volume of print and post generated as well as offering efficiencies in the way documents are printed, collated and distributed.

The transition to a Digital Print & Post room will allow officers to print letters direct to a central location from any networked connection, regardless of their work location.  Centralising print management also aims to reduce internal print volumes and the associated cost to the Council. An efficient Print and Post room would also allow some of the outsourced printing elements to be brought back into the council, further reducing spending.
We would initially be looking at a 3 year contract for licence and support. We would also want indication of training and consultancy costs.


Additional information: Please log onto www.supplyhertfordshire.uk and then click on 'All Opportunities' to 'Express Interest' and download the documentation. 

Is a Recurrent Procurement Type? : No https://in-tendhost.co.uk/supplyhertfordshire/aspx/

releases/0/tender/description:
The Provider is expected to deliver the Provision across the entire Dorset LEP area. Priority areas within the Dorset LEP area expected to have a higher level of eligible Participants are: • Boscombe West (Bournemouth) • East Cliff and Springbourne (Bournemouth) • Boscombe East (Bournemouth) • Kinson South (Bournemouth) • Melcombe Regis (Weymouth & Portland) • Central (Bournemouth) • Newtown (Poole) • Alderney (Poole) • Queen’s Park (Bournemouth) • Westbourne and Westcliffe (Bournemouth).  Service delivery under this contract is expected to commence in October 2016 and continue until September 2019. There will be a further 64 week payment tail. The contract value is £3,373,650 and there is a requirement for a minimum of 1440 Participants to start on this provision. This Provision is voluntary and will aim to target specialist support at Dorset’s Employment and Support Allowance claimants who have mental and/or physical barriers preventing them from securing sustainable employment. Delivery is expected to be individually tailored to meet the needs of the Participant to engage, address barriers to work, and improve their chances of securing and sustaining employment at the earliest opportunity. The Provider must meet ESF specific requirements set by the European Commission and failure to comply can result in a high financial risk for both the Provider and DWP, as funds used inappropriately or for ineligible Participants or purposes and/or where the ESF requirements have not been met are recoverable from Providers. The Provider will use the Provider Referral and Payment (PRaP) system to receive their referrals and to record claimant activity. The Provider will therefore need to have met relevant security requirements when contracts go live. This contract will be for the use of the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP), its Executive Agencies and those Non-Departmental Public Bodies (NDPBs) sponsored by DWP. Further information including a list of such Agencies and Public Bodies can be viewed by selecting ‘Ministerial Departments’ on the Departmental website.

releases/0/tender/title: MAMBA MLE
releases/0/tender/description:
The Artillery Systems Team, part of the UK Ministry of Defence (“MOD”), intends to award SAAB AB the Mobile Artillery Monitoring Battlefield Radar (MAMBA) Mid Life Extension (MLE) Contract commencing  April 2018 addressing end of life equipment/components via technical re-design and re-configuring the Radar equipment within a standardized 12ft container so that the system is vehicle agnostic, this includes obsolescence rectification, equipment modification/re-design, post MLE includes  obsolescence management, maintenance, repair and configuration management of the  Mobile Artillery Monitoring Battlefield Radar (MAMBA) MLE for a total period of 8 years which includes 5 years in-service support . The estimated value of the contract is £38M including in-service support.

It is considered that this contract can be placed using the negotiated procedure without prior publication as permitted by Article 28(1)(e) of Directive 2009/81/EC (Regulation 16(1)(a)(ii) of the Defence and Security Public Contracts Regulations 2011) for technical reasons because only SAAB AB have the specific technological expertise and knowledge , tools and specialist test equipment to carry out the modification work to deliver the required outputs of the MLE project. 

The MAMBA system is a Weapon Locating Radar (WLR) designed, developed and supported soley by SAAB AB.  Only SAAB AB have the necessary and specific technological skills and knowledge of MAMBA to be able to provide the re-design and obsolescence support services required by the MOD to deliver the required outputs of the MLE project through-life. As the Design Authority (DA), SAAB AB have ownership of essential drawings, designs, and associated technical data.  They have the underlying knowledge, skills and expertise, particularly in the area of ballistic algorithms, required for design and modification elements of the contract. SAAB AB are the only company that has the  detailed understanding of the design of MAMBA. 

SAAB AB are the only company that can combine technical re-design with maintenance and repair activities with the requirement for supporting the equipment through-life. Current Out of Service Date is 2016 including obsolescence management and solutions.  No other party has the necessary technical expertise and knowledge required to modify the equipment as the modifications cannot be undertaken without access to proprietary design information.     
As the contracted DA, any modifications developed by a third party would have to be underwritten by SAAB AB resulting in disproportionate technical and safety difficulties for the MOD along with a disproportionate impact on time and cost in order to provide MOD with the necessary assurances the system safety and performance had not been compromised.

Additional information: To view this notice, register as a supplier here:

http://www.contracts.mod.uk/delta/signup.html?userType=supplier

and search for the notice with reference 'UK-Bristol: Repair and maintenance services of military electronic systems.'.

releases/0/tender/title: Hosted Electronic Sales Service
releases/0/tender/description:
The Forestry Commission wishes to replace its current in-house electronic timber sales system, eSales, with a hosted sales solution.  In addition to providing the current eSales functionality, the Forestry Commission wishes to expand the capability of its timber sales system into open ascending price auctions (English Auctions) and the processing of long term timber contracts. There is also a need to develop web-based sales of Niche Market Timber products as well as the expansion of web-based sales to Sundry products such as Permits and other goods and services normally purchased by individuals.   We are seeking a partner to develop these solutions who will host the software on their infrastructure for use by our internal staff and our Customers (Bidders).  The partner must have proven experience in the market

releases/0/tender/title: Multifunctional Devices and Associated Print Services and Supplies
releases/0/tender/description:
EARLY MARKET ENGAGEMENT

This notice is not a call for competition but is an early market engagement exercise to enable Crescent Purchasing Consortium (CPC) to engage with suppliers to better understand the market and explore the potential framework strategy, design and specification.

CPC propose to deliver a seven lot framework as follows:

Lot 1 – Multifunctional/Reprographic Devices and Associated Print Services
Lot 2 – Recycled Technologies
Lot 3 – Managed Print and Document Services
Lot 4 – Specialist Printing Technologies
Lot 5 – Printers, Monitors and Associated Peripherals
Lot 6 – Effective Management of Existing Print Solutions
Lot 7 – Consultancy Services

Suppliers should note that a full list of applicable CPV codes across each of the Lots can be found in the corresponding published EU Prior Information Notice.

To this end, CPC would like to invite suppliers to engage in its' Open Day. It will be hosting two framework Open Day sessions on 17th February 2016; one in the morning and the other in the afternoon. A second day of Open Day sessions will be held on the 18th February should numbers wishing to attend on the 17th be too great for the available places. Sessions will be held at CPCs' offices at Technology House, Lissadel Street, Manchester, M6 6AP. Each session will last approximately 1.5 hours.

If you wish to attend, please register your attendance by contacting j.wood@thecpc.ac.uk. Places will be allocated on a first come first served basis.

Additional information: Suppliers should note that should they wish to provide feedback upon any aspect of the framework strategy,the framework design and/or the specification, such feedback must be sent to j.wood@thecpc.ac.uk, to be received by noon on 25th February 2016. For suppliers not attending the Open Day, presentation materials will be available by emailing a request to j.wood@thecpc.ac.uk.
Suppliers should note that participation or non-participation in the Open Day will not preclude suppliers and/or disadvantage/advantage them in any way from engaging in any future procurement exercise in respect of the framework. Equally suppliers should note that nothing within this notice and or the Open Day shall be relied upon as constituting a contract, agreement or representation that any contract shall be offered in accordance with this PIN.
Please note the framework strategy, design and/or content may change following pre market engagement.

releases/0/tender/title: UOE/2015/062/UEMS/WH - Promethion Early Access Programme
releases/0/tender/description:
The University of Exeter is procuring access to the Oxford Nanopore PromethION Early Access Programme (PEAP). This is a pre-commercial release of a system utilizing nanopore technology to sequence multi-kilobase fragments of DNA. The system will be used to evaluate the suitability of the technology for clinical diagnostic applications as well as method development. To our knowledge no competing system is commercially available at this time 

The specifications of the system contains up to 48 flowcells containing a nanopore sensor array enabling 3000 nanopores each. This allows for up to 144,000 nanopores on the instrument simultaneously. 

The user may deploy as many of the 48 flow cells as they wish at any time to allow for scalable analyses. Within each flow cell, multiple samples may be run separately or the same sample may be run across multiple flow cells for a faster time-to-result.

With real-time analyses, the system needs to be run only for as long as it takes to gather sufficient data to answer the biological question.

releases/0/tender/title: Commercial Strategic Delivery Partner
releases/0/tender/description:
HMRC has an external spend in excess of £1.4 billion annually. Commercial Directorate (CD), who sit within the Chief Finance Officer’s Group (CFO) in HM Revenue & Customs (HMRC) have responsibility for and/or influence over all commercial arrangements covering this spend.

HMRC’s commercial landscape and interaction with the market is changing significantly due to ongoing internal strategic programmes to transform its IT and Estates operations and as a result of increasing Spending Review commitments.

The requirement is for a Commercial Strategic Delivery Partner (CSDP) with the experience and capacity to strengthen current senior commercial leadership and to develop and deliver our Commercial Strategy. 

To deliver this outcome, strategic direction will be set through our Commercial Strategy, which will continue to be driven by HMRC, and the CSDP will required to support and provide guidance on it. We are looking for a supplier that can deliver a partnership approach, improving on things that aren’t working well but nurturing those that do, and be an integral part of the commercial leadership team.
 
The CSDP will provide the additional resources required to deliver business as usual requirements and drive delivery of the strategy in conjunction with existing HMRC commercial leadership and staff. They will collaborate with key internal and external stakeholders, including other HMRC strategic partners. Capability development of, and skills transfer to, both the profession and business areas will be a key requirement of the CSDP to deliver the desired outcome. 

The anticipated outputs/milestones for the CSDP will be based around our Commercial Strategy Delivery Plan, which has the following high level timeline: 
•Apr 16 - develop/implement
•Mar 17 – implement/embed 
•Mar 18 – deliver and exit
HMRC are seeking to engage with organisations and consortia who might be interested in working with the Department to develop its requirements and commercial strategy.
